<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910805-0034</DOCNO><DOCID>910805-0034.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Bell Industries Inc.:   Electronics-Systems Division   To Shut; Charge Announced</HL><DATE>08/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   BI</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>INDUSTRIAL andamp; COMMERCIAL SERVICES, LEASING, CLEANING (ICS)INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL SERVICES (SVC)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Bell Industries Inc. said it will discontinue itselectronics-systems division, resulting in a pretax charge of$3.5 million for the fourth quarter ended June 30.   As a result, the Los Angeles industrial products companyexpects to report a net loss of about $2.6 million, or 44cents a share, compared with net income of $2.9 million, or49 cents a share, a year earlier. Net for the year was about$700,000, or 12 cents a share, down from $8.2 million, or$1.40 a share, a year earlier.</LP><TEXT>   The unit, which makes printed circuit boards for thedefense industry, had sales of about $4.1 million for theyear and an operating loss of about $1.1 million before thenonrecurring charge. Bell attributed the decision todeclining government defense spending, and said the unitwould continue to fill its current order backlog over thenext six to nine months.   Theodore Williams, Bell's president, said sales for thequarter and year were essentially flat compared withyear-earlier results.</TEXT></DOC>